messages.message:
Hi all, I was able to get past the aws credentials errors but I'm running into an error with `control-plane`:

```#25 0.976 error during build:
#25 0.976 Error [ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND]: Cannot find package '@nabla/vite-plugin-eslint' imported from /src/node_modules/.vite-temp/vite.config.ts.timestamp-1753747820944-589821bec2068.mjs
#25 0.976     at Object.getPackageJSONURL (node:internal/modules/package_json_reader:256:9)
#25 0.976     at packageResolve (node:internal/modules/esm/resolve:768:81)
#25 0.976     at moduleResolve (node:internal/modules/esm/resolve:854:18)
#25 0.976     at defaultResolve (node:internal/modules/esm/resolve:984:11)
#25 0.976     at ModuleLoader.defaultResolve (node:internal/modules/esm/loader:780:12)
#25 0.976     at #cachedDefaultResolve (node:internal/modules/esm/loader:704:25)
#25 0.976     at ModuleLoader.resolve (node:internal/modules/esm/loader:687:38)
#25 0.976     at ModuleLoader.getModuleJobForImport (node:internal/modules/esm/loader:305:38)
#25 0.976     at ModuleJob._link (node:internal/modules/esm/module_job:175:49)
#25 0.990 error Command failed with exit code 1.
#25 0.991 info Visit https://yarnpkg.com/en/docs/cli/run for documentation about this command.
#25 ERROR: process "/bin/sh -c [ ! -f package.json ] || yarn build --outDir=/instabase/dist" did not complete successfully: exit code: 1```
Seems unrelated to anything aws related but thought I'd post and see if anyone's seen anything similar

I resolved by running
```rm -rf node_modules yarn.lock
yarn install```
in `~/instabase/cloud-console/admiral/app/client`
and
```cs stop control-plane
cs start control-plane```
Seems like the node package cache was corrupted or something
cc @William Helmrath in case there's a better way to resolve
It’s OK - control plane is not necessary unless you’re working on connectors. Please ignore. In general, ignore errors unless they are actually affecting your work.
Yeah I believe this is a transient error - please don’t remove / modify yarn.lock files though
Got it. Didn't realize `control-plane` wasn't a necessary service, but that should save me a lot of time in the future, thanks for letting me know
